04166nam a22007335i 9780814763520DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147635207 a10.18574/97808147635202doi  a(DE-B1597)547592  a(OCoLC)50745272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a305.3109731 aKann, Mark E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Republic of Men :bThe American Founders, Gendered Language, and Patriarchal Politics /cMark E. Kann. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Culture of Manhood -- t2. The Grammar of Manhood -- t3. The Bachelor and Other Disorderly Men -- t4. The Family Man and Citizenship -- t5. The Better Sort and Leadership -- t6. The Heroic Man and National Destiny -- t7. The Founders' Gendered Legacy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat role did manhood play in early American Politics? In A Republic of Men, Mark E. Kann argues that the American founders aspired to create a "republic of men" but feared that "disorderly men" threatened its birth, health, and longevity. Kann demonstrates how hegemonic norms of manhood-exemplified by "the Family Man," for instance--were deployed as a means of stigmatizing unworthy men, rewarding responsible men with citizenship, and empowering exceptional men with positions of leadership and authority, while excluding women from public life. Kann suggests that the founders committed themselves in theory to the democratic proposition that all men were created free and equal and could not be governed without their own consent, but that they in no way believed that "all men" could be trusted with equal liberty, equal citizenship, or equal authority. The founders developed a "grammar of manhood" to address some difficult questions about public order. Were America's disorderly men qualified for citizenship? Were they likely to recognize manly leaders, consent to their authority, and defer to their wisdom? A Republic of Men compellingly analyzes the ways in which the founders used a rhetoric of manhood to stabilize American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aMenzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aMen. 0aPatriarchyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPatriarchy. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical culture. 0aPolitical sciencezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical science. 0aSex rolezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSex role. 0aSocial rolezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSocial role. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814763520.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK